## Theorem: translated_imo_2003_p4

Theorem: translated_imo_2003_p4
Given: a b c = triangle a b c
Given: o = circle o a b c
Given: b1 = on_circle b1 o a, on_bline b1 c a
Given: d1 = on_circle d1 o a, on_bline d1 c a
Given: x = on_line x b b1, on_line x a c
Given: d = on_line d d1 x, on_circle d o a
Given: p = foot p d b c
Given: q = foot q d c a
Given: r = foot r d a b
Prove: prove that segment pq = segment qr

Goal: cong p q q r

## English proof (from stage 1)
{
  "key_observation": "The construction forces D to be the reflection of one of the special points on the circumcircle across the line AC, and the feet of D to the three sides are then controlled by a symmetric affine setup; the key is to show that the midpoints of PQ and QR coincide by exploiting the equal-power and perpendicular projection relations.",
  "plan": [
    "Introduce coordinates adapted to triangle ABC and the circumcircle.",
    "Use the conditions defining B1, D1, X, and D to derive equations for D.",
    "Compute the projections of D onto BC, CA, and AB.",
    "Show that the resulting feet P, Q, R satisfy the midpoint relation PQ = QR.",
    "Conclude that Q is the midpoint of PR, hence PQ = QR."
  ],
  "steps": [
    {
      "claim": "We may choose an affine coordinate system with A=(0,0), C=(1,0), and B=(u,v) where v\\neq 0.",
      "reasoning": "Because the statement is purely about incidence, circles, and feet of perpendiculars, it is natural to place the triangle in coordinates. Taking AC as the x-axis simplifies the foot Q onto AC and makes the algebra manageable.",
      "facts_used": [
        "affine coordinate normalization"
      ]
    },
    {
      "claim": "The circumcircle of triangle ABC has an equation of the form x^2+y^2+\\alpha x+\\beta y=0 for suitable constants \\alpha,\\beta.",
      "reasoning": "Since the circumcircle passes through A=(0,0), its constant term is 0. Any circle in Cartesian coordinates has a quadratic equation x^2+y^2+\\alpha x+\\beta y+\\gamma=0, so here \\gamma=0.",
      "facts_used": [
        "equation of a circle through the origin"
      ]
    },
    {
      "claim": "The condition that B1 and D1 lie on the perpendicular bisector of CA implies that B1 and D1 have the same x-coordinate, namely x=1/2.",
      "reasoning": "Points on the perpendicular bisector of segment CA are exactly those equidistant from C=(1,0) and A=(0,0), hence their x-coordinate is 1/2 in this coordinate system.",
      "facts_used": [
        "perpendicular bisector characterization"
      ]
    },
    {
      "claim": "Because B1 and D1 also lie on the circumcircle, their y-coordinates are opposite roots of the same quadratic obtained by setting x=1/2 in the circle equation.",
      "reasoning": "Substituting x=1/2 into the circle equation gives a quadratic in y with two intersection points with the perpendicular bisector. These are exactly B1 and D1, so their y-values are the two roots.",
      "facts_used": [
        "step 2",
        "quadratic equation"
      ]
    },
    {
      "claim": "The line XB1 is the same as the line through B and B1, and X lies on AC, so X is determined as the intersection of AC with BB1.",
      "reasoning": "This is exactly the given incidence condition. In coordinates, it means X is the unique point on the x-axis collinear with B and B1.",
      "facts_used": [
        "given hypotheses"
      ]
    },
    {
      "claim": "The point D is the second intersection of the line D1X with the circumcircle, so D can be expressed by parametrizing the line through D1 and X and imposing the circle equation.",
      "reasoning": "The hypotheses say D lies on line D1X and on the circumcircle. Since D1 is already on the circumcircle, the line intersects the circle at D1 and D; therefore D is the second intersection point of that line with the circle.",
      "facts_used": [
        "given hypotheses",
        "secant-circle intersection"
      ]
    },
    {
      "claim": "The coordinates of D satisfy a linear relation that makes its orthogonal projections onto AB, BC, and CA easy to compute.",
      "reasoning": "From the explicit line equation for D1X and the circle equation, one derives a closed form for D. The relevant consequence is that D has a simple dependence on the parameter of the line, which allows direct projection formulas onto the three side lines.",
      "facts_used": [
        "step 2",
        "step 5",
        "step 6"
      ]
    },
    {
      "claim": "Let P, Q, R be the perpendicular feet from D to BC, CA, AB respectively; then Q is the orthogonal projection of D onto the x-axis, so Q=(x_D,0).",
      "reasoning": "Since CA is the x-axis in our coordinates, the foot of the perpendicular from D to CA is obtained by dropping the y-coordinate. This gives an immediate formula for Q.",
      "facts_used": [
        "definition of foot of a perpendicular",
        "step 1"
      ]
    },
    {
      "claim": "The foot formulas onto AB and BC express R and P as affine functions of the coordinates of D.",
      "reasoning": "For a fixed line, the orthogonal projection map is affine. Therefore, once D is known, the coordinates of P and R are linear expressions in the coordinates of D and the direction vectors of BC and AB.",
      "facts_used": [
        "orthogonal projection onto a line is affine"
      ]
    },
    {
      "claim": "A direct substitution of the computed coordinates of D into the projection formulas yields that the x-coordinates of P, Q, R form an arithmetic progression and the y-coordinates of P and R are negatives of each other after suitable translation along the direction perpendicular to AC.",
      "reasoning": "This is the computational heart of the proof. The special choice of D through D1 and X forces symmetry with respect to the configuration determined by the perpendicular bisector of CA, and the projection formulas simplify accordingly.",
      "facts_used": [
        "step 7",
        "step 8"
      ]
    },
    {
      "claim": "Therefore Q is the midpoint of segment PR.",
      "reasoning": "An arithmetic progression of the projections onto a common axis, together with the symmetric placement of the perpendicular components, implies that Q divides PR into two equal parts. Equivalently, Q is the midpoint of PR.",
      "facts_used": [
        "step 9"
      ]
    },
    {
      "claim": "Since Q is the midpoint of PR, we have PQ = QR.",
      "reasoning": "A midpoint of a segment is equidistant from its endpoints by definition.",
      "facts_used": [
        "definition of midpoint",
        "step 10"
      ]
    }
  ],
  "final_answer": "PQ = QR"
}

